  "title": "Reality of Orientation",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "bf5e36572267836b",
      "text": "Perspectivity, reflexivity and recursivity are constitutive for all orientation. Orientation has its 'inner' reality in them and through them it creates the reality that counts as 'outer', without itself making a difference. In the term perspectivity it is grasped that all possibility to 'see' 'something' is bound to a '[[Point of View]]' or 'standpoint' and limited by a '[[Horizon]]'. >> perspectivity reflexivity recursivity orientation horizon"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "70802d7849030099",
      "text": "If an observation is only possible in a perspective, then the perspective in the perspective itself or the consummation of the observation for the respective observation, i.e. the perspectivity or perspectival observability, is not observable. What is observed is something that is seemingly outside the perspective or observation, but is in fact seligated by it. If then perspective tries to focus itself, observation thus tries to observe itself, it cannot focus or observe something else in perspective at the same time. According to the metaphor that has become common and that Luhmann continues to use, it is itself its 'blind spot'. However, point of view and horizon can change, shift spatially speaking, and in this way perspective can also observe itself."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b11126782fc31a17",
      "text": "Point of view and horizon are then probably still the same, but at the same time they have become different. The 'standpoint' is not a 'standing' point and the horizon, […], 'the limiting', not a 'fixed' boundary. With the entry of [[Time]] into them they become paradoxical, but through the temporal metaphor of 'displacement' or 'movement' the paradox is at the same time obscured, made invisible, invisibilized. Thus, perspectives 'with time' become paradoxical to themselves on the one hand, observable on the other. A perspective, having shifted its standpoint and horizon in observing something else, can distinguish itself as earlier and later, thus also observing itself. It then becomes reflexive: the concept of reflexivity also starts from a metaphor of movement, that of 'bending back' (lat. reflectere). In another metaphor it appears as self-reference (from Latin referre, 'to carry back, to direct back, to refer to')."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "009bb458be96a02a",
      "text": "# Perspectivity: Orientation through Perspectives"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e3c181bab15bfc41",
      "text": "Nietzsche uses the term 'perspective' already early on, without giving it any particular philosophical weight at first, then tests it more and more in his notations, in 1884, for example, he speaks of a \"perspective apparatus\", \"which 1) makes a certain standing still 2) simplifies 3) selects and omits possible\" (i.e. of fixing, simplifying and seligifying), simplifying and seligifying), of \"perspectival illusion\" and \"world of perspective\", finally, in 1885, connects the \"'perspectival'\", \"simplifying and falsifying\", with the idea of the will to power and extends it to the \"realm of the inorganic\", physics. Even with the formula of will or wills to power, Nietzsche does not propose a new ontology, but rather an anti-ontology, the paradoxical notion of a unity of mere differences, of a being that is not determined by anything, in which everything incessantly engages with everything and thereby continuously changes, even what is literally 'determined' in the [[Process]]. Wills to power are conceived as perspectives in their opposition, one \"as a temporary condition of existence\" of the other. In such a \"reversal of the perspectival gaze,\" \"'I' 'subject'\" reveal themselves as \"a perspectival illusion,\" as \"an apparent unity in which everything coalesces as in a horizon line.\" >> process gaze"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "19e827512d76f7c9",
      "text": "From there, Nietzsche carries out the utmost abstraction – with which Luhmann will then begin: \"[[Meaning (Sinn)]]\" at all could be mere \"relational meaning\" and as such \"perspective\". In this conceivably high abstraction, first \"the perspectival, the basic condition of all life\" (JGB, KSA 5, 12), then the \"perspective-optics of life\" (JGB, KSA 5, 26), finally \"perspectivism\" becomes a term in the published texts (FW, KSA 3, 593)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "014f7b79803a24b1",
      "text": "Nietzsche probably made approaches to a theory of perspectivism in his notations, but apparently deliberately did not provide such a theory in his published writings. In FW (Aph. 374) he clarifies in his own way what he understands by perspectivism – without using the term again. He explicitly suspends the ontological questioning (\"whether [...] all Dasein is essentially an expository Dasein [or not] – that cannot, how cheaply, be worked out even by the most diligent and scrupulously conscientious analysis and self-examination of the intellect\", FW, KSA 3, 626 f.). Thus, also for his own philosophizing and also at this point, it remains as a starting point that \"the human intellect, in this analysis, cannot avoid seeing itself under its perspective forms and seeing itself only in them\"; it cannot know \"what other kinds of intellect and perspective there might be\" (ibid.)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f179d61e058c21c9",
      "text": "This is true, even if Nietzsche says 'we', for every single intellect. Nevertheless, a perspective experiences its perspectivity in its limitedness by a standpoint and a horizon. Nietzsche says \"corner\" („Ecke“): \"we are today at least far from the ridiculous immodesty to decree from our corner that one may only have perspectives from this corner\" (ibid.) In the impetus of uncertainties one can become aware that one operates in a limited perspective: One can keep reflecting on the uncertainties, but in doing so one does not arrive at certainties. Nietzsche puts it this way: \"The world has rather become 'infinite' to us once again: insofar as we cannot reject the possibility that it includes infinite interpretations\" (ibid., 627). >> infinite"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "498988e82a4d2ca8",
      "text": "[…] \"Once the decision is made,\" Nietzsche had written in JGB (Aph. 107), \"to close the ear even to the best counter-reason. Sign of strong character. Thus an occasional will to stupidity\" (JGB, KSA 5, 92). In JGB (Aph. 188) he called 'stupidity' directly \"the narrowing of perspective,\" \"the need for limited horizons,\" which is \"a condition of life and growth\" (JGB, KSA 5, 110), and in JGB (Aph. 231) he spoke simply of the \"great stupidity that we are\" (JGB, KSA 5, 170). […] The perspectivism of the infinite interpretations does not force to an ontology, but to the abortion of the interpretations, where life needs force to it, and this abortion can be then e.g. also the acceptance of an ontology. >> decision ontology"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b1e09aa3902aa241",
      "text": "Finally, the word of 'devilry', which Nietzsche mentions first, could not only aim at the priests in the service of the great unknown, but also at his own devilry: namely to have proclaimed a counter-god, the \"God Dionysus\", as the god of his philosophizing (JGB, KSA 5, 238): Dionysus as a god who does not reassure about the possibility of infinite interpretations, but, on the contrary, always reminds us of them anew. Nietzsche 'constructs' him from the perspective of his perspectivism as the god of his perspectivism – thereby precautionarily occupying the place that would otherwise be quickly reoccupied elsewhere. The proclamation of Dionysus as the god of philosophizing is supposed to arm one to reflect again on vital stupidity and folly where one cannot avoid surrendering to them (\"let us come to the aid of our 'God' with all our 'devils'!\", it says in JGB, KSA 5, 163) and thus to strengthen \"honesty\". But even against honesty one must remain suspicious. For \"what do we know of ourselves in the end? [...] Our honesty, we free spirits, – let us see to it that it does not become our vanity, our finery and pomp, our limit, our stupidity! Every virtue tends to stupidity, every stupidity to virtue\" (ibid.). >> honesty"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "601fc8613d9cf10b",
      "text": "Luhmann uses the term 'perspective' frequently, for instance in Sinn als Grundbegriff der Soziologie when introducing the \"social dimension\" of \"meaning\", in Soziale Systeme, Die Wissenschaft der Gesellschaft, and Die Gesellschaft der Gesellschaft then increasingly frequently, but until the end unterminologically. […]"
