      "type": "edit",
      "id": "e3c181bab15bfc41",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "e3c181bab15bfc41",
        "text": "Nietzsche uses the term 'perspective' already early on, without giving it any particular philosophical weight at first, then tests it more and more in his notations, in 1884, for example, he speaks of a \"perspective apparatus\", \"which 1) makes a certain standing still 2) simplifies 3) selects and omits possible\" (i.e. of fixing, simplifying and seligifying), simplifying and seligifying), of \"perspectival illusion\" and \"world of perspective\", finally, in 1885, connects the \"'perspectival'\", \"simplifying and falsifying\", with the idea of the will to power and extends it to the \"realm of the inorganic\", physics. Even with the formula of will or wills to power, Nietzsche does not propose a new ontology, but rather an anti-ontology, the paradoxical notion of a unity of mere differences, of a being that is not determined by anything, in which everything incessantly engages with everything and thereby continuously changes, even what is literally 'determined' in the [[Process]]. Wills to power are conceived as perspectives in their opposition, one \"as a temporary condition of existence\" of the other. In such a \"reversal of the perspectival gaze,\" \"'I' 'subject'\" reveal themselves as \"a perspectival illusion,\" as \"an apparent unity in which everything coalesces as in a horizon line.\" >> process gaze"
      },
      "date": 1681334863781
