    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "014f7b79803a24b1",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "014f7b79803a24b1",
        "text": "Nietzsche probably made approaches to a theory of perspectivism in his notations, but apparently deliberately did not provide such a theory in his published writings. In FW (Aph. 374) he clarifies in his own way what he understands by perspectivism – without using the term again. He explicitly suspends the ontological questioning11 (\"whether [...] all Dasein is essentially an expository Dasein [or not] - that cannot, how cheaply, be worked out even by the most diligent and scrupulously conscientious analysis and self-examination of the intellect\", FW, KSA 3, 626 f.). Thus, also for his own philosophizing and also at this point, it remains as a starting point that \"the human intellect, in this analysis, cannot avoid seeing itself under its perspective forms and seeing itself only in them\"; it cannot know \"what other kinds of intellect and perspective there might be\" (ibid.)."
