      "type": "add",
      "id": "b1e09aa3902aa241",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "b1e09aa3902aa241",
        "text": "Finally, the word of 'devilry', which Nietzsche mentions first, could not only aim at the priests in the service of the great unknown, but also at his own devilry: namely to have proclaimed a counter-god, the \"God Dionysus\", as the god of his philosophizing (JGB, KSA 5, 238): Dionysus as a god who does not reassure about the possibility of infinite interpretations, but, on the contrary, always reminds us of them anew. Nietzsche 'constructs' him from the perspective of his perspectivism as the god of his perspectivism - thereby precautionarily occupying the place that would otherwise be quickly reoccupied elsewhere. The proclamation of Dionysus as the god of philosophizing is supposed to arm one to reflect again on vital stupidity and folly where one cannot avoid surrendering to them (\"let us come to the aid of our 'God' with all our 'devils'!\", it says in JGB, KSA 5, 163) and thus to strengthen \"honesty\". But even against honesty one must remain suspicious. For \"what do we know of ourselves in the end? [...] Our honesty, we free spirits, - let us see to it that it does not become our vanity, our finery and pomp, our limit, our stupidity! Every virtue tends to stupidity, every stupidity to virtue\" (ibid.)."
